  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is prohibited and is considered a serious criminal offense in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the funds appear legitimate and thus integrate them into the financial system without arousing suspicion.\n\n### Key Points About Money Laundering Prohibition:\n1. **Illegality**: Money laundering is illegal under national and international laws. It is a crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates other criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption.\n\n2. **International Efforts**: Organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have adopted and implemented FATF recommendations into their legal frameworks.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Businesses and individuals involved in money laundering can face prosecution and significant reputational damage.\n\n4. **Prevention and Detection**: Financial institutions, businesses, and governments are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and prevent money laundering activities. This includes customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities to authorities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is strictly prohibited, and those involved in such activities can face serious legal consequences.",
